<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="60630" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="60630">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="60630">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Syscia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Syscia augustae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="60630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="augustae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="60630">Syscia augustae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Wheeler W.M., 1902) were found on an induced grassland in Jalpan De La Sierra, Queretaro, at 2575 m a.s.l., 18.3
<normalizedToken originalValue="ºC">°C</normalizedToken>
of amt and 45.5 mm/cm2 of amp. This species has been recorded in all the U.S. southern border States. In Mexico, they are recorded in Baja California Peninsula, Sonora, Sinaloa, Nuevo 
<normalizedToken originalValue="León">Leon</normalizedToken>
, Tamaulipas, Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave and Oaxaca. Recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Borowiec, Marek" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="60630" pagination="1 - 280" refId="B6311212" refString="Borowiec, Marek, 2016. Generic revision of the ant subfamily Dorylinae (Hymenoptera, Formicidae). ZooKeys 608: 1 - 280" title="Generic revision of the ant subfamily Dorylinae (Hymenoptera, Formicidae)" volume="608" year="2016">Borowiec (2016)</bibRefCitation>
recorded this species in southeast Asia, in Borneo, Japan and India.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="60630" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="60630">Biology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="60630">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Syscia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Syscia augustae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="60630" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="augustae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="60630">Syscia augustae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a subterranean, blind ant with predatory behaviour (
<bibRefCitation author="Wheeler, W. M." journalOrPublisher="The Biological Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="60630" pagination="181 - 191" refId="B6312419" refString="Wheeler, W. M., 1902. An American Cerapachys, with remarks on the affinities of the Cerapachyinae. The Biological Bulletin 3 (5): 181 - 191" title="An American Cerapachys, with remarks on the affinities of the Cerapachyinae" volume="3" year="1902">Wheeler 1902</bibRefCitation>
). These ants can be found in the leaf litter, under stones and in branches on the soil, usually in moist habitats (
<bibRefCitation author="MacKay, W. P." journalOrPublisher="Edwin Mellen Press, Lewiston, NY" pageId="0" pageNumber="60630" refId="B6311658" refString="MacKay, W. P., Mackay, E., 2002. The ants of New Mexico (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Edwin Mellen Press, Lewiston, NY" title="The ants of New Mexico (Hymenoptera: Formicidae)" year="2002">MacKay and Mackay 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
